Question 1¶

a) No¶

The least squares method (or minimal least squares) is specifically designed to find the minimum value for this estimator. In the case of least squares, the cost function or loss function being optimised is the sum of squared differences between the predicted and actual values. As a result the minimum MSE is equal to the minimal least squares.

b) Model Error¶

The mean squared estimator measures the average squared difference between the predicted values and the actual values. This is the model or reducible error that the model has not been able to fit. The irreducible error on the other is not captured by the MSE. It arises from factors that are beyond the model's control, such as inherent noise in the data, unpredictable events, or unknown variables that influence the target variable.

Question 2¶

Entropy quantifies the disorder or randomness of the class labels within a subset of data.

a) False¶

Entropy measures the impurity or disorder within a dataset. High entropy indicates that the partition is impure with a more mixed distribution of data points within that partition. This implies there is no clear separation of the data and that there is no majority class.

b) True¶

High entropy means that there is a high level of impurity in the classes. The data cannot be easily defined or separated and the characteristics of each partition are mixed. In the context of decision trees, high entropy means that we cannot, with a high probability, assign new data points to a partition with high entropy.

Hypothesis¶

Choice of ticker

  • I have chosen the Gold Futures ticker which is traded on COMEX.
  • This will trade at a small premium to the actual price of gold but will be an accurate proxy to all the underlying properties of the commodity that I am looking for.
  • This is because of the cost-of-carry pricing model, the futures price should be the same as the current spot price plus the cost of carrying (or storing) the underlying asset until the maturity of the futures contract. If the spot and futures prices are out of alignment, arbitrage activity would occur and rectify the imbalance.
  • Futures positions are marked to market daily, and, as the underlying instrument's price moves, this will be reflected in the future price.

My hypothesis around gold is that I am looking going to be targeting momentum & near to T price moves. Gold is considered a flight to safety asset. In the historical down periods of the past 10 years (COVID), we can see big up moves in Gold prices (section 3.5) as market uncertainty increased.

My overall hypothesis is that Gold should display some good properties to implement a successful trading strategy on it.

Feature Engineering/ Creation¶

Features are also known as an independent variable which are used to determine the value of the target variable. We will create features and target (label) from the raw dataset.

In [13]:
# create features
def create_features(frame):
    df = frame.copy()

    # Gold Price features
    df['OC'] = df['ADJ CLOSE'] / df['OPEN'] - 1
    df['HL'] = df['HIGH'] / df['LOW'] - 1
    df['LRET'] = np.log(df['ADJ CLOSE'] / df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(1))
    df['RET'] = (df['ADJ CLOSE'] - df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(1))/df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(1)
    df['MOM'] = df['ADJ CLOSE']- df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(1)
    df['PRET'] = np.log(df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(1)/ df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(2))

    for i in [7]:
        df['LRET' + str(i)] = df['LRET'].rolling(i).sum()
        df['RET' + str(i)] = (df['ADJ CLOSE'] - df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(i))/df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(i)
        df['MA' + str(i)] = df['ADJ CLOSE'].rolling(i).mean()
        df['EWMA_' + str(i)] = df['ADJ CLOSE'].ewm(span = 7, adjust = False).mean()
        df['OC'+ str(i)] = df['OC'].rolling(i).mean() 
        df['HL'+ str(i)] = df['HL'].rolling(i).mean() 
        df['MOM'+ str(i)] = df['ADJ CLOSE']- df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(i)
        df['PRET'+str(i)] = np.log(df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(1)/ df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(i+2))
               
    df['LABEL'] = df['ADJ CLOSE'].shift(-1)    
    # drop NaN values
    df.dropna(inplace=True)
    return df

# Create Data Frame
df = create_features(df)

# Create X Data Frame
X = df.drop(['ADJ CLOSE','OPEN', 'HIGH', 'LOW', 'CLOSE', 'VOLUME', 'LABEL','matching'], axis=1)

Y = np.array(df['LABEL'])

  • Because I have have created derivatives of the original price features (High, Low, Open, Close, Adjusted close), I can drop them as they will not add much more additional value.
  • Although Volume will contribute to the demand of Gold and therefore price, I am not going to include it in my model.
  • My dependent variable is the T+1 adjusted close price. This is the signal I am going to try and predict in my machine learning model. I have labeled this as my LABEL.

In the above, I have created a number of features around different price mechanisms and signals.

  1. Intraday Price Range.
$$ OC = Open - Close \hspace{3cm} [1] $$$$ HC = High - Low \hspace{3cm} [2] $$
  1. Log Returns.
$$ LRET = \ln (\frac{P_t}{P_{t-i}}) \hspace{3cm} [3] $$

where $ P_t $ is Adjusted Close price.

  1. Past Returns
$$ RET = \frac{P_t - P_{t-i}}{P_{t-i}} \hspace{3cm} [4] $$
  1. Gap between trading days.
$$ GAP = \frac{Open_t}{Close_{t-i}} -1 \hspace{3cm} [5] $$
  1. Simple moving average
$$ MA = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=0}^{n=1} P_{t-i} \hspace{3cm} [6]$$
  1. Exponentially weighted moving average
$$ EWMA = EWMA_{t-1} + \mathcal{a}[P_t - EWMA_{t-1}] \hspace{3cm} [7]$$
  1. Momentum
$$ MOM = P_t - P_{t-i} \hspace{3cm} [8] $$
  1. Past Returns
$$ PRET = \frac{P_{t-1} - P_{t-i+1}}{P_{t-i+1}} \hspace{3cm} [9] $$

Comment on Scaling¶

Normalisation presupposes that our data has a Gaussian distribution whereas Standardisation (via the minmax scaler) will convert our data between a range of [1,-1].

I will use Standardisation throughout my next steps of feature selection. This is because I cannot comment on the distribution of my features at this point.

Embedded Methods for feature Selection¶

  • Lasso and Ridge are both regularising methods, they aim to regularise complex models by introducing penalty factors. They are great at reducing overfitting, handling multicollinearity, or just automatic feature engineering.
In [23]:
class Regression:
    def __init__(self, X, Y, testsize=0.20): ### TEST Size, 20%, this is user defined

        self.X = X
        self.Y = Y
        self.testsize = testsize
        
        # split training and testing dataset
        self.X_train, self.X_test, self.y_train, self.y_test = train_test_split(self.X,
                                                                                self.Y, 
                                                                                test_size=self.testsize, 
                                                                                random_state=0, 
                                                                                shuffle=False)
    
    # fit and predict
    def fit_predict(self, estimator, transformer, alpha=None, l1_ratio=None):
        
        try:
            # subsume estimators and transformer into a pipeline
            model = Pipeline([
            ('scaler', transformer), 
            ('regressor', estimator)
            ])

            # fit/train model
            model.fit(self.X_train, self.y_train)

            # predict lables
            y_pred = model.predict(self.X_test)

        except Exception as e:
            print(str(e))

        return model, model['regressor'].intercept_, model['regressor'].coef_, y_pred

    # evaluate metrics
    def eval_metrics(self,model, y_pred):

        # evaluate metrics
        mse = mean_squared_error(self.y_test, y_pred, squared=True)
        rmse = mean_squared_error(self.y_test, y_pred, squared=False)
        r2train = model.score(self.X_train, self.y_train)
        r2test = model.score(self.X_test, self.y_test)

        return mse, rmse, r2train, r2test

    # plot coefficients as a function of lambda
    def plot_coeff(self, modelname):

        coef = []
        model = Regression(self.X, self.Y, 0.20)
        alpha_range = np.logspace(2, -2, 200)

        if modelname == 'Lasso':
            for i in alpha_range:    
                coef.append(model.fit_predict(Lasso(alpha=i, random_state=0), MinMaxScaler())[2])

        elif modelname == 'Ridge':
            alpha_range = np.logspace(6, -2, 200)
            for i in alpha_range:    
                coef.append(model.fit_predict(Ridge(alpha=i, random_state=0), MinMaxScaler())[2])

        elif modelname == 'ElasticNet':
            for i in alpha_range:    
                coef.append(model.fit_predict(ElasticNet(alpha=i, random_state=0), MinMaxScaler())[2])
        
        # Plot Coefficients
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))
        ax = plt.axes()
        
        ax.plot(alpha_range, coef)
        ax.set_xscale('log')
        ax.legend(feature_names, loc=0)
        # ax.set_xlim(ax.get_xlim()[::-1])  # reverse axis
        ax.set_title(f'{modelname} coefficients as a function of the regularization')
        ax.set_xlabel('$\lambda$')
        ax.set_ylabel('$\mathbf{w}$')

        return plt.show()

Lasso Regression - L1 Cost Function¶

  • The Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator (LASSO) is a variation of linear regression. In Lasso, the loss function is minimized by limiting the sum of absolute values of the model coefficients where the L1 penalty term is added to the Mean Square Error (MSE). The L1 penalty term not only shrinks the coefficents, but shrinks some of them to zero and that is very useful for feature selection.

where, is the regularization penalty that is added to the RSS. The here is a hyperparameter that can be tuned.

Ridge Regression - L2 Cost function¶

In ridge regression, the cost function is altered by adding a L2 penalty which is equivalent to squaring the magnitude of the coefficients. The Ridge regression shrinks the coefficients and helps to reduce the multi-collinearity. When 0, the cost function becomes similar to the linear regression cost function.

When $ \infty $ this shrinks the coefficients of the dependent variables. This is another hyperparameter to tune.

ElasticNet Regression - Combination of L1 and L2 Cost Function¶

ElasticNet combines the properties of both Lasso and Ridge regression. It penalizes the model using both the L1 and L2 norm.

where 0 1.

Elastic net is same as lasso when =1,

and ridge when = 0. For other values of , the penalty term interpolate between L1 and L2 norm of the coefficient.

Wrapper Methods for subset selection¶

Evaluates on a specific machine learning algorithm to find optimal features

SHAP Method¶

The SHAP method uses a game theoretic approach. It can be described as the average marginal contribution of a feature value across all possible coalitions. SHAP deconstructs a prediction into a sum of contributions from each of the model's input variables.

Variables are sorted by their mean absolute SHAP value in descending order with the most important variables at the top. Each dot corresponds to one price return in my dataset. The beeswarm plot shows how the different variable expressions of each price affect the prediction of the ML model towards a T+1 movement in the Gold price. Positive SHAP values indicate a change in the expected model prediction to an increase in the T+1 Gold price.

In [38]:
def forward_selection(data, target, significance_level=0.05):
    initial_features = data.columns.tolist()
    best_features = []
    while (len(initial_features)>0):
        remaining_features = list(set(initial_features)-set(best_features))
        new_pval = pd.Series(index=remaining_features)
        for new_column in remaining_features:
            model = sm.OLS(target, sm.add_constant(data[best_features+[new_column]])).fit()
            new_pval[new_column] = model.pvalues[new_column]
        min_p_value = new_pval.min()
        if(min_p_value<significance_level):
            best_features.append(new_pval.idxmin())
        else:
            break
    return best_features

Backward Selection¶

In [40]:
def backward_elimination(data, target,significance_level = 0.05):
    features = data.columns.tolist()
    while(len(features)>0):
        features_with_constant = sm.add_constant(data[features])
        p_values = sm.OLS(target, features_with_constant).fit().pvalues[1:]
        max_p_value = p_values.max()
        if(max_p_value >= significance_level):
            excluded_feature = p_values.idxmax()
            features.remove(excluded_feature)
        else:
            break 
    return features

Draw downs¶

In [45]:
def drawdown(returns):
    cumulative = (returns + 1).cumprod()
    running_max = np.maximum.accumulate(cumulative)
    return (cumulative - running_max) / running_max

The max drawdown differs from the drawdown by tracking the maximum drawdown of a 30-day rolling window of returns.

In [46]:
def max_drawdown(returns):
    return np.min(drawdown(returns))

rets.rolling(30).apply(max_drawdown).plot(kind="area", color="salmon", alpha=0.5)
Out[46]:
<Axes: xlabel='Date'>

The 30day rolling drawdown should be more gentle yet it remains quite significant across the piece.

My General comments are that draw downs appear more common in the period 2013 up until 2020 where gold was evidently used as a safe haven throughout the COVID pandemic. I will try and create a balanced class as the data reflects this.

My classes are already largely balanced. When setting up my model, I will balance the classes in my target that can be seen below. Therefore, I do not have to worry about class imbalance.

\begin{equation} Y_t=\begin{cases} +1, & \text{if $ P_{t+1} > Med(P_t) $ }.\\ 0, & \text{$ Otherwise $}. \end{cases} \end{equation}

Where $ Med(P_t) $ is the median price of all prices in the series.

This should balance my two classes evenly.

Precision¶

My precision for my buy signal is particularly strong. The model is prediction in my test results is giving signals of only buying. In this case, this is becasue the next days up move is greater than the median price move across the whole dataset.

$$ Precision = \frac{TP}{(TP + FP)} $$

Recall¶

Recall is the ability of a classifier to find all positive instances. It is very good at signalling when to buy (0.998) which is important in the context of a Long Only Trend following Strategy.

$$ Recall = \frac{TP}{(TP+FN)} $$

Support¶

Furthermore, my support statistics clearly show an imbalance in the dataset. In the future I would try and test the data throughout different testing sets.

GridSearch using multiple evaluation metrics¶

In [66]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
In [67]:
scoring = {"AUC": "roc_auc", "Accuracy": make_scorer(accuracy_score)}

# Setting refit='AUC', refits an estimator on the whole dataset with the
# parameter setting that has the best cross-validated AUC score.
# That estimator is made available at ``gs.best_estimator_`` along with
# parameters like ``gs.best_score_``, ``gs.best_params_`` and
# ``gs.best_index_``
gs = GridSearchCV(
    DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42),
    param_grid={"min_samples_split": range(2, 403, 20)},
    scoring=scoring,
    refit="AUC",
    n_jobs=2,
    return_train_score=True,
)
gs.fit(Xnew, Y_bal)
results = gs.cv_results_
In [68]:
plt.figure(figsize=(13, 13))
plt.title("GridSearchCV evaluating using multiple scorers simultaneously", fontsize=16)

plt.xlabel("min_samples_split")
plt.ylabel("Score")

ax = plt.gca()
ax.set_xlim(0, 402)
ax.set_ylim(0, 1)

# Get the regular numpy array from the MaskedArray
X_axis = np.array(results["param_min_samples_split"].data, dtype=float)

for scorer, color in zip(sorted(scoring), ["g", "k"]):
    for sample, style in (("train", "--"), ("test", "-")):
        sample_score_mean = results["mean_%s_%s" % (sample, scorer)]
        sample_score_std = results["std_%s_%s" % (sample, scorer)]
        ax.fill_between(
            X_axis,
            sample_score_mean - sample_score_std,
            sample_score_mean + sample_score_std,
            alpha=0.1 if sample == "test" else 0,
            color=color,
        )
        ax.plot(
            X_axis,
            sample_score_mean,
            style,
            color=color,
            alpha=1 if sample == "test" else 0.7,
            label="%s (%s)" % (scorer, sample),
        )

    best_index = np.nonzero(results["rank_test_%s" % scorer] == 1)[0][0]
    best_score = results["mean_test_%s" % scorer][best_index]

    # Plot a dotted vertical line at the best score for that scorer marked by x
    ax.plot(
        [
            X_axis[best_index],
        ]
        * 2,
        [0, best_score],
        linestyle="-.",
        color=color,
        marker="x",
        markeredgewidth=3,
        ms=8,
    )

    # Annotate the best score for that scorer
    ax.annotate("%0.2f" % best_score, (X_axis[best_index], best_score + 0.005))

plt.legend(loc="best")
plt.grid(False)
plt.show()

What the above shows is that I have effectively optimised the algorithm to the best of my abilities. The AUC represents the probability that a random positive example is positioned to the right of a random negative example. Increasing the split of decisions doesn't increase this any further in my example.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion to the above trading strategy, there are negative returns to this trading strategy. This is because of the imbalance of my testing set of data's up moves each day were largely all greater than the median change over the whole dataset. This caused my trading strategy to be worse than the buy and hold by failing to signal "no buy" on the single down day in my testing set.

However, this does contribute to the hypothesis that gold is a safe haven & should be bought and held for long term returns. Gold has also been used as an inflation in the more recent years hence it is trading at such a significant premium to the previous 8 years.

Future improvements would involve switching the commodities in my original input and see if the price features I have identified translate across to different commodity markets in the model. This would be a useful exercise to perform to see if the momentum carries and the model can predict more down days.
